At the other end of the spectrum, fringe elements on the extreme fringes of feminist and ethnocentric politics might view divorce as a solution to a 'problem' in the society, probably due to the economic and material gains derived from divorce in the ethnonationalist model of family. More middle of the road views would revolve around the opinion that each divorce should be viewed according to social, economic, cultural, ethnic and gender considerations, making it difficult to arrive at an informed conclusion at this stage.

SITUATION ANALYSIS

As the Parsons ethnonationalist model of the family provides an additional and useful analytical tool, it is important to examine the Fijian family and its prospects for either breakdown or kanabu into bonded septs within the wider social structure. In other words, the Fijian family system fulfils the criterial requirements of the Parsons ethnonationalist model. It is a clan society and has the potential to be a nationstate. The other major group of Fijian families, the Matanivanua, are ethnonationalist.
